Lafayette Street (Elm Street), north from but not including East Houston Street, showing the street under construction after the demolition of buildings which formerly stood there. The construction of the street necessitated the razing of many buildings in a northerly direction from Elm Street, which terminated at a point slightly south of Jersey Street, to Lafayette Place, which commenced at Great Jones Street. The new thoroughfare was named Lafayette Street several years later.
November 5, 1900.

Board of Transportation Photograph.

William B. Parsons Collection.

Lafayette Street (Elm Street), north from but not including East Houston Street, showing construction work in progress on the Interborough Rapid Transit Co. (I.R.T.) subway, after the demolition of buildings which formerly stood there. Lafayette Street was created by the joining of Elm Street, which terminated at a point slightly south of Jersey Street with Lafayette Place, which commenced at Great Jones Street. This necessitated the razing of many houses which stood between the above mentioned two thoroughfares. The new street was given its present name several years later.

November 12, 1900.

Board of Transportation Photograph.
William B. Parsons Collection.

Lafayette Street (Elm Street), north from but not including East Houston to and including East 8th Streets, showing the street under construction. The building of the street necessitated the razing of many houses in a northerly direction from Elm Street, which terminated at a point slightly south of Jersey Street to Lafayette Place, which commenced at Great Jones Street. The new thoroughfare received its present name several years later, under which was constructed the Interborough Rapid Transit Co. (I.R.T.) subway.

January 3, 1901.

Board of Transportation Photograph.

William B. Parsons Collection.

300 Mulberry Street, adjoining the N.E. corner of East Houston Street. This structure shown is the old New York Police Headquarters; the inscription across same being, Central Department of the Metropolitan Police.

About 1910.

Social Conditions in Manhattan: The kitchen of a 4 room flat at No. 284 Mulberry Street and some of the apartments, 12 occupants (including 10 children). The rental for this space is .25. Note its clean appearance. Undoubtedly published by the New York Evening World on this date.

January 2, 1924.

Gift of New York World.

The view shows building on Houston Street (East), razed in order to continue the construction of the Eighth Ave., Municipal Subway System.

February 21, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

39 East Houston Street, south side, west from Mulberry (left), to Lafayette (right) Streets, showing the Puck Building, erected sometime between the 2nd and 3rd quarters of the 19th Century. This structure occupies the block bounded by East Houston to Jersey Streets, and Mulberry to Lafayette Streets. It is an edifice in the Italian Renaissance style and is occupied by the J. Ottman Lithographing Co., foremost establishment of its kind on the American continent and the publishers of the magazine "Puck," a periodical, satirizing political and social groups. The clearance, shown in the foreground was caused by demolitions on the north side of East Houston Street, during the construction of the Eighth Ave. Subway. Also shown, on the left, is an extensive view southward on Mulberry Street.
